    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2366890">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2366890">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2366890)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2366890">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zacharia-h" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2204215); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2204215&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252591" alt="Zacharia H" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2204215)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zacharia-h" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2204215); return false;" >Zacharia H</a></span> <span class="odate time_1440948435 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Aug 2015 15:27</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2366890">
									

<p>I felt like the story called for a persistent character, not a bunch of anonymous D-Class who get killed at the end of every test and replaced - and a protagonist should (in most cases) be at least remotely likable.</p>
<p>That's why I didn't want the reader to hate D-5081. He may be a criminal, but he's also just a kid who made some very bad choices. The way I see it, he already had a history - but after being caught in a stolen car with dozens of bags of some very nasty chemicals stuffed under the seats, he was finally going in for life. When he got the offer from the Foundation (in desperate need of more guinea pigs after a recent containment breach), it sounded like the perfect deal.</p>
<p>So, going through the story, the reader is able to become just a <em>teensy</em> bit attached to him, because he's clearly not evil - just childish, and a little stupid. Maybe you'll even feel sorry for him at the end.</p>

							</div>

								
					
