				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/littlesallydigby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1910986); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1910986&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252592" alt="LittleSallyDigby" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1910986)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/littlesallydigby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1910986); return false;" >LittleSallyDigby</a></span> <span class="odate time_1455596831 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">16 Feb 2016 04:27</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2457905">
									

<p>&quot;It was waiting for this.&quot; doesn't have an attribution (SCP-2209, D-5081, Dr. Davids), nor is it formatted as a transcript of non-spoken events (with the brackets). I'm not sure whether this is a typo, or deliberate interface screw.</p>
<p>Overall I enjoyed this. My headcanon: there are multiple subsystems within the AI that don't always agree on things. The user interface that talks to D-5081 and identifies itself is indiscriminately user-friendly, because that's its job&#8230; but the randomizer isn't. (Maybe this is because the randomizer can generate responses to its own queries, and therefore sees the user as superfluous?) Things only go wrong when D-5081 requests a change without knowing what it is or specifying what it should be, and of course they go totally to shit when the random scenario is selected.</p>

							</div>

								
					
